habitat_description: Larus canus winters along the Pacific coast of the conterminous U.S., foraging in water, along river mouths, near the surf-line, in estuaries, on sandy and cobble beaches, and on mudflats (Cogswell, 1977; Tangren, 1982; Moskoff and Bevier, 2002; RBCM, 2010). Mew gulls also forage in pasture and recently plowed cropland near the coast (Cogswell, 1977; Colwell and Dodd, 1995), as well as sewage outfalls, sewage treatment ponds (Moskoff and Bevier, 2002), and garbage dumps (Buckley, 1987). The species can also be found farther inland, along river valleys (DeVillers et al., 1971; RBCM, 2010), up to elevations of 1280 m (Moskoff and Bevier, 2002). Mew gulls are seldom seen farther than 1 or 2 km from shore (Moskoff and Bevier, 2002).
